  "opinion": "As a woman who's been driving deliveries for over a decade in Washington DC, I've seen how science often feels out of reach for people like me—those without advanced degrees or college access. The gender gap in science isn't just about fewer women in labs or engineering firms; it's about the whole ecosystem that makes science seem exclusive. When I talk to my friends who work in tech or research, they say the same thing: 'You can't just drop into this world—you need a specific background.' That’s the real problem. I’ve noticed that in my community, especially among people from my parents' generation, there’s a lot of skepticism about science being something only 'smart' people can do. It’s not about intelligence—it’s about opportunity. And that’s why we need to address it. We should start by making science accessible to everyone, not just those with college degrees. For example, my neighbors who are teachers or community organizers often say they’ve seen kids drop out of STEM because they don’t think they belong. So, instead of pushing for more women in science, we need to build the foundation so anyone can enter the field. This means creating programs that teach science in a way that’s relevant to daily life—like using real-world problems we face in our communities. My own experience as a delivery driver has shown me that science isn’t just for classrooms or labs; it’s about solving problems in the streets. If we can make science feel like something that matters to people in their everyday lives, then the gap won’t be a barrier but a bridge.",
